ORACLE AUTONOMY KILL-SWITCH — EXAMPLE / DOCUMENTATION

This file is an EXAMPLE. It is named `KILL-SWITCH.example`, so it does NOT halt
anything. The live kill-switch is a file named exactly `KILL-SWITCH` (no
extension) in this same folder: Meta.nosync/Autonomy/KILL-SWITCH

HOW IT WORKS
------------
_tools/actions.py checks for the presence of the live `KILL-SWITCH` file as the
very FIRST step of any autonomous action, before reading autonomy.yml and before
checking `enabled`. If the file exists, the action is refused immediately and an
action_event row is logged with result "killed". This overrides `enabled: true`
and every allowlist entry — it is an unconditional, instant hard stop.

The contents of the file do not matter. Presence is the signal. A short note
explaining who pulled the switch and why (like this one) is good hygiene but is
not parsed.

TO HALT THE ORACLE
------------------
    touch "Meta.nosync/Autonomy/KILL-SWITCH"

The next headless harness run (and any in-session autonomous action) will
hard-stop and log the event. Interactive use by a human is unaffected — the
kill-switch only gates AUTONOMOUS actions.

TO RESUME
---------
    rm "Meta.nosync/Autonomy/KILL-SWITCH"

Removing the file lets actions.py proceed to the normal allowlist / caps checks
again. Resuming does not re-enable anything that was not already enabled in
autonomy.yml; it only clears the override.

WHEN TO USE IT
--------------
- The oracle is behaving unexpectedly during headless runs.
- You are doing maintenance and want no unattended writes.
- A connector or lane is in a bad state and you want to freeze activity.
- Any time you want certainty that nothing acts on its own, right now.

NOTE
----
The kill-switch is the fastest, most reliable off-switch, but it is not the only
guard: autonomy is OFF by default (autonomy.yml `enabled: false` with empty
allowlists), and every action is additionally bounded by blast_radius_caps. The
kill-switch exists for the case where you want to stop everything instantly,
without editing autonomy.yml.
